          "id": "osei_report_envelope",
          "type": "notes3",
          "name": "Loss Adjustment Report (Fairbridge Associates)",
          "takeable": false,
          "readable": true,
          "text": "FAIRBRIDGE ASSOCIATES — Loss Adjustment Report — MC-2023-ALBE-007\nPrepared by: David Osei, Senior Loss Adjuster\n\nTOTAL CLAIMED LOSS: £8,200,000\n\n(a) Incident response costs: £1,400,000 — FULLY COVERED regardless of warranty status.\n(b) Business interruption: £4,800,000 — CONTESTED. Meridian argues a portion of the outage represents pre-existing SIS recertification obligation (deferred firmware patch). My assessment: the full 6-week outage is causally attributable to the incident. Emergency recertification is a consequence of the attack, not a pre-existing scheduled obligation.\n(c) Physical damage: £1,600,000 — COVERED under affirmative cyber clause.\n(d) Third-party — Trent Water: £400,000 — PROVISIONAL pending Trent Water forensic findings.\n\nWARRANTY DEDUCTION ANALYSIS:\nW-07 breach is causally connected to the IT-to-OT lateral movement pathway. A proportionate deduction of 20-25% applied to items (b) and (c) — approximately £1.5-1.6M — is legally defensible under the Insurance Act 2015.\n\nMY RECOMMENDATION:\nPosition A (full coverage) is commercially generous but legally exposed.\nPosition B (partial with ~25% deduction on BI and physical damage) is the most defensible position.\nPosition C (decline) is not recommended — would likely result in litigation and regulatory criticism.\n\nEstimated settlement at Position B: approximately £6.1-6.3M.",
